{"id":"2305.00503","submitter":"Martin Winter","authors":"Anna M. Limbach, Martin Winter","title":"Characterising Clique Convergence for Locally Cyclic Graphs of Minimum\n  Degree $\\delta\\ge 6$","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.CO","license":"http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/","abstract":"  The clique graph $kG$ of a graph $G$ has as its vertices the cliques (maximal\ncomplete subgraphs) of $G$, two of which are adjacent in $kG$ if they have\nnon-empty intersection in $G$. We say that $G$ is clique convergent if\n$k^nG\\cong k^m G$ for some $n\\not= m$, and that $G$ is clique divergent\notherwise.\n  We completely characterise the clique convergent graphs in the class of (not\nnecessarily finite) locally cyclic graphs of minimum degree $\\delta\\ge 6$,\nshowing that for such graphs clique divergence is a global phenomenon,\ndependent on the existence of large substructures. More precisely, we establish\nthat such a graph is clique divergent if and only if its universal triangular\ncover contains arbitrarily large members from the family of so-called\n\"triangular-shaped graphs\".\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 30 Apr 2023 15:16:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-05-02"}
